{"title_page": "Sony CLI\u00c9 PEG-NZ90", "text_new": "[[File:Sony-CLIE-PEG-NZ90.jpg|thumb|right|200px|A '''Sony CLI\u00c9 PEG-NZ90''' Personal Entertainment Organiser model featuring a respectable multimedia specification.]]\nThe Sony Clie '''PEG-NZ90''' was a flagship handheld PDA announced by Sony in January 2003.<ref>{{cite web |title=Hands-on Review: Sony Clie NZ90 |url=http://www.palminfocenter.com/news/5065/sony-clie-nz90-review/ |accessdate=14 September 2019}}</ref> This model was feature-packed, further improving on the capabilities of the [[Sony CLI\u00c9 NX Series|NX series]] models. Like its predecessors, this handheld had a vertical clamshell swivel-screen form factor, and was powered by a 200mhz [[Intel XScale]] CPU, running the [[Palm OS]] (version 5).\n\nThe main improvement to this model, were the addition of a Xenon camera flash, and a higher-resolution 2MP built-in CCD camera with both autofocus and a macro mode. This camera was state-of-the-art for the time; capable 2MP cameras with flash were not commonly seen in mobile devices until several years later, such as the [[Sony Ericsson K750]] which was released in 2005.\n\nThe device was criticised for only featuring 16MB of storage, which was seen as poor value for the high retail price.\n\nIn Japan, the NZ90U model featured a contactless [[FeliCa]] card reader IC. This enabled users to check the balance on an [[Edy]] (prepaid-money) card, or a [[Japan Rail Pass]] (prepaid travel) card.<ref>{{cite web |title=Sony Announces Mid-Range Handheld in Japan |url=http://www.brighthand.com/news/sony-announces-mid-range-handheld-in-japan/ |accessdate=14 September 2019}}</ref>\n\nOver time, a number of these devices have suffered from design defects. In particular, the Sony CCD used had a tenancy to fail over time, due to humidity affecting down the bonding substrate used in the CCD assembly. This [[Failure_mode_and_effects_analysis|failure mode]] affected many other CCD-based products at the time, including the [[Sony CLI\u00c9 NX Series#PEG-NX73V_&_PEG-NX80V|Clie NX80V PDA]], as well as a number of Sony digital camera models<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.macworld.com/article/1047412/ccd.html |title=Digital-camera makers to replace faulty image sensors |accessdate=11 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Widespread CCD problems in consumer imaging products |url=https://www.imaging-resource.com/badccds.html |website=www.imaging-resource.com |accessdate=11 April 2020}}</ref>. The LCD displays used on this model also had a tendency to be easily damaged.\n\n==Specifications==\nSpecifications from Palm Info Center.<ref>{{cite web |title=Hands-on Review: Sony Clie NZ90 |url=http://www.palminfocenter.com/news/5065/sony-clie-nz90-review/ |accessdate=14 September 2019}}</ref>\n\n*[[Palm OS]]: 5.0\n*CPU: Intel [[XScale]] PXA250 200&nbsp;MHz\n*Memory: 16MB RAM (11MB avail.), 16MB ROM\n*Display: 480 x 320 transflective back-lit TFT-LCD, 16bit Colour (65k colours)\n*Sound: Internal audio amplifier, Rear speaker, Mono Mic, Stereo Headphone out.\n*External Connectors: USB\n*Expansion: Memory Stick Pro, MSIO, Compact Flash (Type II), Wireless LAN (In form of Compact Flash expansion card sold separately by Sony)\n*Wireless: Infrared IrDA\n*Battery: Rechargeable Li-Ion Polymer (1200 mAh)\n*Size & Weight: 5.4 (H) x 2.8 (W) x 0.6-0.9 (D) inches, 10.3 oz.\n*Color: Silver\n\n== See also ==\n[[Sony CLI\u00c9 UX Series]] - The successor to the NZ series.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.palminfocenter.com/news/5065/sony-clie-nz90-review/ NZ90 Review at Palm Info Center]\n\n{{Sony CLI\u00c9 devices}}\n{{Sony Corp}}\n\n[[Category:Sony CLI\u00c9]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Sony-CLIE-PEG-NZ90.jpg|thumb|right|200px|A '''Sony CLI\u00c9 PEG-NZ90''' Personal Entertainment Organiser model featuring a respectable multimedia specification.]]\nThe Sony Clie '''PEG-NZ90''' was a flagship handheld PDA announced by Sony in January 2003.<ref>{{cite web |title=Hands-on Review: Sony Clie NZ90 |url=http://www.palminfocenter.com/news/5065/sony-clie-nz90-review/ |accessdate=14 September 2019}}</ref> This model was feature-packed, further improving on the capabilities of the [[Sony CLI\u00c9 NX Series|NX series]] models. Like its predecessors, this handheld had a vertical clamshell swivel-screen form factor, and was powered by a 200mhz [[Intel XScale]] CPU, running the [[Palm OS]] (version 5).\n\nThe main improvement to this model, were the addition of a Xenon camera flash, and a higher-resolution 2MP built-in CCD camera with both autofocus and a macro mode. This camera was state-of-the-art for the time; capable 2MP cameras with flash were not commonly seen in mobile devices until several years later, such as the [[Sony Ericsson K750]] which was released in 2005.\n\nThe device was criticised for only featuring 16MB of storage, which was seen as poor value for the high retail price.\n\nIn Japan, the NZ90U model featured a contactless [[FeliCa]] card reader IC. This enabled users to check the balance on an [[Edy]] (prepaid-money) card, or a [[Japan Rail Pass]] (prepaid travel) card.<ref>{{cite web |title=Sony Announces Mid-Range Handheld in Japan |url=http://www.brighthand.com/news/sony-announces-mid-range-handheld-in-japan/ |accessdate=14 September 2019}}</ref>\n\nOver time, a number of these devices have suffered from design defects. In particular, the Sony CCD used had a tenancy to fail over time, due to humidity affecting down the bonding substrate used in the CCD assembly. This [[Failure_mode_and_effects_analysis|failure mode]] affected many other CCD-based products at the time, including the [[Sony CLI\u00c9 NX Series#PEG-NX73V_&_PEG-NX80V|Clie NX80V PDA]], as well as a number of Sony digital camera models<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.macworld.com/article/1047412/ccd.html |title=Digital-camera makers to replace faulty image sensors}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Widespread CCD problems in consumer imaging products |url=https://www.imaging-resource.com/badccds.html |website=www.imaging-resource.com |accessdate=11 April 2020}}</ref>. The LCD displays used on this model also had a tendency to be easily damaged.\n\n==Specifications==\nSpecifications from Palm Info Center.<ref>{{cite web |title=Hands-on Review: Sony Clie NZ90 |url=http://www.palminfocenter.com/news/5065/sony-clie-nz90-review/ |accessdate=14 September 2019}}</ref>\n\n*[[Palm OS]]: 5.0\n*CPU: Intel [[XScale]] PXA250 200&nbsp;MHz\n*Memory: 16MB RAM (11MB avail.), 16MB ROM\n*Display: 480 x 320 transflective back-lit TFT-LCD, 16bit Colour (65k colours)\n*Sound: Internal audio amplifier, Rear speaker, Mono Mic, Stereo Headphone out.\n*External Connectors: USB\n*Expansion: Memory Stick Pro, MSIO, Compact Flash (Type II), Wireless LAN (In form of Compact Flash expansion card sold separately by Sony)\n*Wireless: Infrared IrDA\n*Battery: Rechargeable Li-Ion Polymer (1200 mAh)\n*Size & Weight: 5.4 (H) x 2.8 (W) x 0.6-0.9 (D) inches, 10.3 oz.\n*Color: Silver\n\n== See also ==\n[[Sony CLI\u00c9 UX Series]] - The successor to the NZ series.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.palminfocenter.com/news/5065/sony-clie-nz90-review/ NZ90 Review at Palm Info Center]\n\n{{Sony CLI\u00c9 devices}}\n{{Sony Corp}}\n\n[[Category:Sony CLI\u00c9]]\n", "name_user": "Pinchies", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sony_CLI%C3%89_PEG-NZ90"}
{"title_page": "Kobutori Jiisan", "text_new": "[[File:Japanese Fairy Book - Ozaki - 277.png|thumb|240px|The demons pull off the lump from the old man's cheek]]\n{{nihongo|\"'''Kobutori Jiisan'''\"|\u3053\u3076\u3068\u308a\u3058\u3044\u3055\u3093|Kobutori j\u012bsan|extra2=literally \"Lump-removing Old Man\"}} is a [[Japanese folktales|Japanese Folktale]] about an old man who lost his [[Neoplasm|lump]] (or [[Sebaceous cyst|wen]]) after joining a party of demons (''[[oni]]'') celebrate and [[dance]] for a night.\n\nThe tale is a rendition of a tale about a woodcutter ([[firewood]]-gatherer) from the early 13th century anthology ''[[Uji Sh\u016bi Monogatari]]''.\n\n== Textual notes ==\nThe tale, which may be known in Japanese as {{nihongo||\u7624\u53d6\u308a|\"'''Kobutori'''\"}},<ref name=iwaya-j-1927/> {{nihongo||\u7624\u53d6\u308a\u723a\u3055\u3093|\"Kobutori Jiisan\"}},<ref name=seki1956/> or {{nihongo||\u7624\u53d6\u308a\u723a\u3044|\"'''Kobutori jijii'''\"}},<ref name=lanham&shimura1967/> is arguably among the top ten native [[fairy tale]]s that are frequently recounted to children in modern Japan.<ref name=lanham&shimura1967/><!--\"Jiisan\" with -san would be the polite form of address, appropriate for children's books or classroom reading often written in polite language. \"Jijii\" may be scholarly but can be taken as rude.-->\n\n=== English translations ===\nThe tale was translated as '''''The Old Man and the Devils''''' (1886)<ref name=jacobs/> by [[James Curtis Hepburn]].<ref name=sharf/>{{efn|This title was No. 7 of the English-translated Japanese Fairy Tale Series, produced by [[wood-block printing]] on [[crepe paper]] by [[Hasegawa Takejir\u014d]].<ref name=sharf/> The illustrator for the volume is indeterminate.<ref name=kyoto-u-hepburn-tr/><!--Though ascribed to Kobayashi Eitatsu by some srcs.-->}}\n\nHepburn translated the ''[[oni]]'' as \"devils\" where a more modern editions might give \"demons\" or \"ogres\", but it was commonplace during this time period to replace native Japanese concepts with equivalent Christian ones in these translated stories.<ref name=guth/>{{efn|Cf. ''[[Shippeitaro]]'' where the temple becomes a \"chapel\".}}\n\n\"'''How an Old Man Lost his Wen'''\" by [[Yei Theodora Ozaki]] (1903) was a retelling baseds on a published Japanese text edited by {{illm|Iwaya Sazanami|ja|\u5dcc\u8c37\u5c0f\u6ce2}}.<ref name=herring/> Though not a literal translation by her own admission, it has been assessed as deserving more credit as to its fidelity.<ref name=fraser/>{{efn|Lucy Fraser, lecturer in Japanese at the University of Queensland, Australia.}}\n\nThere is another translation also using Sazanami Iwaya as the Japanese source. \"'''The Old Man with the Wen'''\" found in ''Iwaya's Fairy tales of old Japan'' (1914) credited to [[Hannah Riddell]] as translator,<ref name=iwaya-j-1927/> although each tale was originally printed separately in 1903,<ref name=rogala/> and was it was a translating effort by several women.<ref>{{harvp|Herring |1988 |p=100}}. Others such as Fanny Greene.</ref>\n\nA similar version \"'''Story of the Man with the Wen'''\", which names the locale as \"mount Taiko\", was printed in the ''Transactions of the Japan Society'' in 1885.<ref name=goodwin/> A more recent  translation effort is \"'''Lump off, Lump On'''\" (1987) by [[Royall Tyler (academic)|Royall Tyler]],<ref name=\"tyler\"/>\n\n== Plot ==\nThere was an old man with a lump<ref name=\"hepburn\"/><ref name=\"tyler\"/> (or [[Sebaceous cyst|wen]]<ref name=\"ozaki\"/><ref name=riddell1914/>) on the right side of his face.<ref>{{nihongo||\u7624|kobu}} is \"lump\" or \"wen\". The tale says it grows on the right side ({{harvp|Hepburn|1888}}, and {{harvp|Iwaya|1927}} in Japanese),  but was overlooked by {{harvp|Riddell tr.|1914}}.</ref>{{efn|In {{harvp|Iwaya|1927}}, {{harvp|Riddell tr.|1914}}, and {{harvp|Ozaki|1903}}, the swelling was a source irritation and he tried to remove it consulting the physician.}}\n\nOne day he went into the [[mountain]] to cut wood, and was caught in the rain. He took refuge in the [[Tree hollow|hollow]] of a tree.{{Refn|group=\"lower-alpha\"|{{sfnp|Iwaya|1927|p=136}}; A {{nihongo|hollow|\u3046\u308d}} by the root of a large tree. In {{harvp|Ozaki|1903}}, the old man first sees a charcoal-burner's hut. There are additional details in {{harvp|Iwaya|1927|p=136\u2013137}} (and {{harvp|Riddell tr. |1914}}): the old man sees a flash of lightning and chants \"[[Kuwabara kuwabara]]\". He then expected to see {{nihongo|\"the other wood-cutters\"|\u4ed6\u306e\u6728\u6a35\u9054}}. Note that in the medieval tale he is unequivocably a wood-cutter who earned his living selling firewood.<ref name=shirane/>}} He was soon to witness a gathering of strange beings nearby, some one-eyed and some mouth-less.<ref name=\"hepburn\"/><ref name=\"ozaki\"/><ref name=\"tyler\"/>{{efn|One-eyed individuals are illustrated in {{harvp|Hepburn|1888}} but the details is wanting in the {{harvp|Iwaya|1927}} Japanese and {{harvp|Riddell tr. |1914}}.}} They were the ''[[oni]]''<ref>{{harvp|Iwaya|1927|pp=137\u2013139}} Japanese text. First referred to as {{nihongo|[[bakemono]]|\u5316\u3051\u7269}} then interchangeably as {{nihongo|[[oni]]|\u9b3c}}.</ref> ([[demon]]s or [[ogre]]s; \"devils\" being the Christendom equivalent<ref name=guth/>).{{efn|Rendered \"demons\" ({{harvp|Ozaki|1903}}, {{harvp|Riddell tr. |1914}});  \"devils\" ({{harvp|Hepburn|1888}}; \"monsters\" ({{harvp|Tyler|1987}}).}}\n\n[[File:Japanese Fairy Book - Ozaki - 281.png|thumb|240px|The second old man returns home with two lumps on his face]]\nThe oni created a great bonfire as light as day. The began to drink [[sake]] wine,{{sfnp|Iwaya|1927|pp=138\u2013139}} sing and dance. They old man overcame his fears and was lured to join the dance. His dance greatly entertained the oni, who wanted him to return the next day<ref>{{harvp|Iwaya|1927|p=142}}. {{harvp|Riddell tr. |1914}} {{harvp|Ozaki|1903}}</ref> (or \"always\"<ref name=\"hepburn\"/>) for an [[encore]]. To ensure the old man's return, the oni wanted keep charge of some valuable possession, and of all things, decided the old man's lump should be taken as [[pledge (law)|pledge]]. They then proceed to remove the unwanted tumor.<ref> In {{harvp|Iwaya|1927|p=142}}, {{harvp|Riddell tr. |1914}}, {{harvp|Ozaki|1903}}, the demons arrive at their own  conclusion that the lump is some sort of lucky charm, without the old man's contrivance. In {{harvp|Hepburn|1888}}, the old man tells a clever lie that the lump was something he would not willingly part with.</ref> The old man was elated to find the lump gone, with not a remnant of it remaining,<ref name=\"hepburn\"/> and no soreness in the cheek where it was removed.<ref>{{harvp|Iwaya|1927|p=143}}, {{harvp|Riddell tr. |1914}}, {{harvp|Ozaki|1903}}.</ref>\n\nThere lived next door an old man who had a big lump on his left cheek.<ref>{{harvp|Hepburn|1888}}; {{harvp|Iwaya|1927|p=143}} {{harvp|Riddell tr. |1914}} {{harvp|Ozaki|1903}}</ref> When he heard his [[neighbourhood|neighbor]]'s story about losing the lump, he wanted to emulate, and therefore asked to take the place of performing in front of the oni, and the neighbor yielded him the opportunity. The left-lump old man went to the same tree hollow, and when the oni assembled, the chief demon was particularly eagerly awaiting.<ref>{{harvp|Iwaya|1927|p=145}}: {{nihongo||\u982d\u306e\u5927\u9b3c|kashira no \u014doni|extra2=literally \"chief big-demon\"}} {{harvp|Riddell tr. |1914}}: \"King Demon\", {{harvp|Ozaki|1903}}: \"the demon chief\".</ref> Unfortunately, the left-lump old man did not have the same skill in the art of dancing, and was a disappointment to the demons, who bid him to take back his lump and leave. And the demons slapped on the piece of flesh which stuck to the clean side of his face,<ref>{{harvp|Hepburn|1888}}: \"brought the lump and stuck it on the other side of his face\".</ref>{{Refn|{{harvp|Iwaya|1927|p=146}}: {{nihongo||\u7624\u3092\u3070\u982c\uff08\u307b\u3063\uff09\u307a\u305f\u3081\u304c\u3051\u3066\u6253\u3061\u3064\u3051|extra2=literally \"struck aiming at the cheek\"}}, and{{harvp|Iwaya|1911}} has the  {{nihongo||\u304a\u3057\u3064\u3051\u308b|extra2=literally \"press at\", which {{harvp|Ozaki|1903}} and {{harvp|Riddell tr. |1914}} translate as \"threw at\". The medieval tale actually agrees: {{nihongo||\u4eca\u7247\u65b9\u306e\u9854\u306b\u6295\u3052\u4ed8\u3051\u305f\u308a\u3051\u308c\u3070|extra2=tr. \"threw the wen at the old man's other cheek\"}}.<ref name=shirane/>}}. So this old man returned home chagrined, now with two lumps on his face.<ref name=\"hepburn\"/><ref>{{harvp|Iwaya|1927|p=146}}: the two lumps looked like {{nihongo|[[calabash]]|\u74e2\u7baa|hy\u014dtan}}, which {{harvp|Ozaki|1903}} closely renders as \"Japanese gourd\".{{harvp|Riddell tr. |1914}} gives \"ends of a dumbell\".</ref>\n\n== Analysis ==\n\n===Origins===\n\nThis folktale can be traced to the tale collection ''[[Uji Sh\u016bi Monogatari]]'' compiled in early 13th century.<ref name=goodwin/><ref name=shirane/> The medieval version has been translated as \"'''How Someone Had a Wen Removed by Demons'''\". Here the man explicitly \"made his living gathering [[firewood]]\". The medieval concludes with a one-liner moral cautioning against envy.<ref name=shirane/>\n\n===Variants===\nA variant called {{nihongo|The tumor doubled|\u7624\u4e8c\u3064|Kobu futatsu}}, where the protagonist priest has a [[tumor]] over the eye, was collected by [[Kunio Yanagita]]. The locality of the tale was not given.<ref name=yanagita1952/>\n\nThe version given by [[Algernon Bertram Freeman Mitford|A. B. Mitford]] in 1871 \"'''The Elves and the Envious Neighbour'''\" features two men with a wen on the forehead, and the second visitor earns another wen on top of his own. And it was not because of poor dancing or companionship, just mistaken identity. Mitford\"s version also concludes with a moral against envy.<ref name=mitford1871/>\n\n=== Analogue ===\n\n[[Charles Wycliffe Goodwin]] noticed that the Japanese \"Kobutori\" tale was analogous to the Irish \"[[The Legend of Knockgrafton]]\", reporting his finding in 1875, though this was not printed for the public at large until 1885.<ref name=goodwin/> The Irish had been published by [[Thomas Crofton Croker]] in 1824 or 1825, and Goodwin first noticed the similarity after reading Mitford's brief version of the Japanese tale, but subsequently obtained a fuller version of the story which he printed in his paper.<ref name=goodwin/> The resemblance of \"The Legend of Knockgrafton\" to  the Japanese folktale was also noted by [[Joseph Jacobs]] in 1894.<ref name=jacobs/>\n\n== Explantory notes ==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n;Citations\n{{Reflist|30em|refs=\n\n<ref name=fraser><!--[[Lucy Fraser]] redirects to Frazer-->Fraser, Lucy. \"[https://books.google.com/books?id=pLReDwAAQBAJ&pg=PT10 Foreword]\" in Ozaki, Yei Theodora (2018). ''Japanese Folktales: Classic Stories from Japan's Enchanted Past''. Tuttle. {{isbn|1462920101<!--, 9781462920105-->}}.</ref>\n\n<ref name=goodwin>{{citation|last=Goodwin |first=Charles Wycliffe Goodwin |author-link=Charles Wycliffe Goodwin |title=On Some Japanese Legends |journal=Transactions The Asiatic Society Of Japan |volume=3 |number=Part 2 |year=1885 <!--18 January 1875 to 30 June 1875-->|url=https://archive.org/details/in.ernet.dli.2015.70888/page/n169/mode/2up/ |pages=46\u201352<!--45\u201362-->}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=guth>{{citation|last=Guth |first=Christine M. E. |author-link=<!--Christine M. E. Guth--> |editor-last=Pellizzi |editor-first=Francesco |editor-link=<!--Francesco Pellizzi--> |title=Hasegawa's fairy tales: Toying with Japan |work=Res: Anthropology and Aesthetics |volume=53/54 |place= |publisher=Harvard University Press |year=2008 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=RXnBTZK1DvgC&pg=PA273 |pages=273<!--267\u2013282--> |isbn=087365840X<!--, 9780873658409-->}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"hepburn\">{{harvp|Hepbur