im.<!--33-48--> |jstor=538416}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=mitford1871>{{citation|editor-last=Mitford |editor-first=A. B. |editor-link=Algernon Bertram Freeman Mitford |chapter=The Elves and the Envious Neighbour |title=Tales of Old Japan In Two Volumes |location=London |publisher=Macmillan |year=1894 |chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=p-BRAAAAcAAJ&pg=PA276 |pages=276\u2013277}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"ozaki\">{{harvp|Ozaki|1903}} tr. \"[https://books.google.com/books?id=V_RyPbadxJgC&pg=PA273 How an Old Man Lost his Wen]\". pp. 273\u2013282.</ref>\n\n<ref name=rogala>{{cite encyclopedia|ref=harv|last=Rogala |first=Jozef |title=A Collector's Guide to Books on Japan in English |publisher=Taylor & Francis |year=2001|pages=102\u2013103 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=pUmua1V7-9oC&pg=PA102 |isbn=9781873410912}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=riddell1914>{{harvp|Riddell tr. |1914}} Part 10 of 12. \"The Old Man with the Wen\".</ref>\n\n<ref name=seki1956>{{cite book|ref=harv|editor-last=Seki|editor-first=Keigo |editor-link=Keigo Seki |chapter=16. Kobutori Jiisan |script-chapter=ja:16 \u3053\u3076\u3068\u308a\u723a\u3055\u3093 |title=Nihon no mukashibanashi dai-ichi (Kobutori jiisan, Kachikachi yama) |script-title=ja:\u65e5\u672c\u306e\u6614\u3070\u306a\u3057 \u7b2c1 (\u3053\u3076\u3068\u308a\u723a\u3055\u3093\u30fb\u304b\u3061\u304b\u3061\u5c71) |publisher=Iwanami<!--1956--> |year=1927 |url= |pages=|language=ja}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=sharf>{{citation|last=Sharf |first=Frederic Alan |author-link=<!--Frederic Alan Sharf--> |title=Takejiro Hasegawa: Meiji Japan's Preeminent Publisher of Wood-block-illustrated Crepe-paper Books |place=Salem |publisher=Peabody Essex Museum |year=1994 |series=Peabody Essex Museum Collections, vol. 130 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=1yTrAAAAMAAJ%22devils%22}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=shirane>{{citation|editor-last=Shirane |editor-first=Haruo |editor-link=Haruo Shirane|chapter=A Collection of Tales from Uji |title=Traditional Japanese Literature: An A